8. Changes in PaymentBookingService

Remove this:

private record PayProcDetails(
        String gtwMapsId,
        String payProcId,
        String payProcType) {
}

Import the DTO instead.

import com.yourorg.transaction.dto.PayProcDetails;

Then update buildPaymentInitiationRequest().

Old:

request.setGtwMapsId(payProcDetails.gtwMapsId());
request.setPayProcId(payProcDetails.payProcId());
request.setPayProcType(payProcDetails.payProcType());

New:

request.setGtwMapsId(payProcDetails.getGtwMapsId());
request.setPayProcId(payProcDetails.getPayProcId());
request.setPayProcType(payProcDetails.getPayProcType());

Everything else stays exactly the same because all methods already return

return new PayProcDetails(
        gtwMapsId,
        payProcId,
        payProcType);

which also works for a normal DTO since we've added an all-arguments constructor.

Alternative (Recommended for your project)

Since your project already appears to use Lombok builders extensively (for example, PaymentBookingResponse.builder()), you can make PayProcDetails consistent with the rest of the codebase:

@Getter
@Setter
@Builder
@NoArgsConstructor
@AllArgsConstructor
public class PayProcDetails {

    private String gtwMapsId;
    private String payProcId;
    private String payProcType;
}

Then you can create instances like:

return PayProcDetails.builder()
        .gtwMapsId(gtwMapsId)
        .payProcId(payProcId)
        .payProcType(payProcType)
        .build();

This style is commonly used in Spring Boot projects and is more consistent with the rest of your codebase.


